******
[1] China
Date: Tue 6 May 2008
Source: Rednet.cn, Links notice, China Daily report [edited]
<http://news.rednet.cn/c/2008/05/06/1500337.htm>


Hand-foot-mouth epidemic still spreads
--------------------------------------
The number of Chinese children infected with hand-foot-mouth disease
(HFMD) continues to rise, with reported cases exceeding 8531 on Mon 5
May 2008. All were below the age of 6, with the majority being under
2. Altogether [at least] 25 children have died of the disease. Tests
have confirmed 24 of the deaths were triggered by the virus known as
enterovirus 71 (EV71).

According to the Guidelines Regarding Prevention and Control of HFMD
published on the Ministry of Health website, HFMD can be caused by a
host of intestinal viruses, but EV71 and the coxsackievirus A16 (Cox
A16) were the most common.

Anhui Province, in east China, and Guangdong Province, south China
were the worst hit areas. 22 of the deaths occurred in Fuyang, a city
in northwestern Anhui, and the rest happened in Guangdong. These 2
regions were followed by Beijing, Jiangsu, Hunan, and Hubei,
according to statistics released by local health departments.

In Anhui alone, 622 new cases were reported on Saturday [3 May 2008],
including 362 in Fuyang, driving up the number of children with HFMD
to 5151 in Anhui. Beijing has recorded at least 1010 cases of the
disease, while Guangdong registered 925 cases as of Sunday [4 May 2008] .

Both EV71 and Cox A16 can cause HFMD, which usually starts with a
slight fever followed by blisters and ulcers in the mouth and rashes
on the hands and feet. Those sickened by EV71 often show serious
symptoms. It can also lead to meningitis, encephalitis, pulmonary
edema, and paralysis in some children. There is no vaccine.

Saying reports of HFMD could increase in the next few months, the
Health Ministry issued a circular late last month [April 2008]
requiring better management and surveillance of the disease. The
ministry asked hospitals for daily reports on the disease, and for
local health departments to report emergencies promptly and increase
investment in research into the disease.

[Byline: Sharon Lee]

