******
[2] China
Date: Mon 5 May 2008
Source: The Canadian Press, Associated Press (AP) report [edited]
<http://canadianpress.google.com/article/ALeqM5hJd29FRftSKGRh4eMPrFxFjKxXHw>


China says hand-foot-mouth disease spreading among children
-----------------------------------------------------------
More than 11 900 children have been reported sick with
hand-foot-mouth disease (HFMD) in China, and at least 26 of those
cases have died, a state news agency said. 24 of the deaths, in the
central province of Anhui and Guangdong province in the south, have
been blamed on enterovirus 71, one of several viruses that cause the
disease, the official Xinhua News Agency said Monday [5 May 2008]. 2
other children -- one in Guangdong and another in the coastal
province of Zhejiang -- have also died of hand-foot-mouth disease but
it wasn't immediately clear which strain of virus killed them, it said.

The Xinhua News Agency said 10 212 children had been reported
infected in the hardest-hit areas, including the provinces of Anhui,
Guangdong, Zhejiang, and the capital Beijing. All were below the age
of 6 and most were under the age of 2, it said. The total number of
infections reported nationwide by Monday [5 May 2008] was 11 905,
Xinhua said, with smaller outbreaks in Hebei, Jiangsu, Hunan, Hubei,
Shaanxi, Jiangxi, and Henan provinces and in the city of Chongqing.

Although nearly all the deaths have been blamed on enterovirus 71
(EV71), it was not immediately clear how many of the overall
infections were traced to that virus. Zhejiang's provincial health
bureau said on its website that only 9 of its 1198 cases had tested
positive for EV71. Chongqing said none of its 42 infections have been
confirmed to be cause by EV71.

Xinhua said the jump in cases was due in part to a new regulation
from the Ministry of Health classifying hand-foot-mouth disease among
those that have to be reported to the central government. The agency
said a majority of the cases were reported in Anhui province, where
5840 cases were reported, nearly all of them in the fast-growing city
of Fuyang.

Enterovirus [71] causes a severe form of hand-foot-mouth disease with
symptoms including fever, mouth sores, and rashes with blisters. It
is easily spread by sneezing or coughing. The viruses mainly strike
children ages 10 and younger. Some cases can lead to fatal swelling
of the brain.

The illness is not related to foot-and-mouth disease, which afflicts
livestock. There is no vaccine or specific treatment, but most
children affected by mild forms of the disease typically recover
quickly without problems. The World Health Organization (WHO) says
the virus normally peaks in June and July so there could be an
increase in infections as the weather warms.

