******
[4] Taiwan
Date: Tue 6 May 2008
Source: The China Post [edited]
<http://www.chinapost.com.tw/taiwan/national/national%20news/2008/05/06/155077/CDC-reports.htm>


CDC reports 2nd death from enterovirus
--------------------------------------
Public health officials reported the death of a 3-year-old boy in
southern Kaohsiung yesterday [5 May 2008]; the 2nd fatal enterovirus
case this year. They urged all parents and schoolteachers to be more
vigilant against enterovirus [infection], as temperatures in Taiwan
continue to rise into the summer months. Chou Jih-haw, deputy
director of the Center for Disease Control (CDC) under the Department
of Health (DOH), said that the latest victim was a boy aged 3 years
and 4 months who had probably been infected by his 5-year-old sister.

On 11 Apr 2008, the boy developed a fever, with rashes and sores in
his mouth, and he was checked into the hospital with spasms the
following day [12 Apr 2008], Chou said. The boy lapsed into a coma
shortly after he was admitted, and died 5 days later despite efforts
to save him, Chou said. An investigation found that the boy's sister
also had an enterovirus infection, and had been admitted to the
hospital on 13 Apr 2008. But she fully recovered because her case was
not that serious.

"Children under 3 years old are most vulnerable to the disease
because they have no antibodies, making them a high risk group in
serious cases of enterovirus, especially in cross infection
situations," Chou said. The 1st enterovirus death occurred in March
[2008] in Yunlin County, southwestern Taiwan, the CDC reported.

Health officials at the CDC said that the number of confirmed serious
cases of enterovirus has reached 60 this year [2008], and among them
there have been 2 deaths; 7 other patients remain in intensive care,
while one has been hospitalized for about 4 months due to
encephalitis complications.

Enterovirus infections can be deadly for young children. The virus
enters the body through the gastrointestinal tract and often moves on
to attack the nervous system, leading to symptoms of fever, muscle
aches, and aseptic or viral meningitis. In a massive outbreak in
Taiwan in 1998, 405 children were infected and 78 of them eventually
died. The most recent outbreak came in 2005, with 145 children
infected and 15 dying from the virus.

DOH officials said people should maintain good personal hygiene by
frequently washing their hands. Parents and teachers at elementary
schools and kindergartens should especially supervise young children
to clean their hands in southern Taiwan during warmer weather, they
said. Young children should also be kept away from places with big
crowds, they advised.

